 <div><br><span class="pageheader">Secrets of Faydwer Creature Feature</span><BR><HR>The Secrets of Faydwer expansion, due out in November 2007, is going to have some sweet new monsters!  Intelligent and aggressive steamworks, hundred-foot tall wandering metal guardians, cursed insane spirits, and vicious lycanthropic orcs are just a few of the new NPCs designed for this expansion.  These guys are just waiting to see how tough the heroes of Norrath really are.<p>

I got an inside glimpse into the creation and the lore behind some of the newest inhabitants of Norrath, thanks to Ryan Barker, EverQuest Senior Designer.<p>

<strong><font size=4>The Design Process</strong></font><p>

<i>EQV: Can you describe the design process for moving these creatures from someone's imagination into the live game?</i><p>

RB: When a new NPC is created, it starts as a set of descriptions written by the design team and then handed off to a concept artist who will draw a sketch of what the character might look like.  Design will then give feedback based on the concept art and changes are often made.  After adjustments, the concept is approved and the model creation begins.  Once the model is built and textured, it’s handed off to an animator who will create the various movement, attack and emote animations.  Once the animations are done, designers can begin using the model to populate zones and give them special abilities and attributes, which is what you eventually see in game.<p>

<i>EQV:  Does one person design each creature?</i><p>

RB: The designs for the characters are a collaborative effort by the design team during the initial stages of designing an expansion.  Often an idea will come from a combination of ideas from several people, so it’s never really one person’s idea.<p>

<i>EQV:  Do you design the creature for the zone, or the zone for the creature?</i><p>

RB: Sometimes a really good idea for a monster necessitates the creation of a zone built for them, and sometimes we’ll brainstorm ideas for monsters based on a zone theme.<p>

<strong><font size=4>The Creatures</strong></font><p>

Now to introduce you to some of the very scary characters that will soon be roaming the lands of Norrath!<p>

In these exclusive graphics from SOE, you can see the creation sequence for each creature as it goes goes from concept to live.<p>

The first figure in each sequence is the initial drawing by the artist.  The next step for completion is to create a wire frame image, or model render, so the creature can move in three dimensions.  The last image you see in each sequence is the live game version, transformed from the initial sketch.<p>

SOE has also linked some video clips for each creature, so you can see them in action!<p>

<strong><center><font size=4>WEREORCS</strong></font></center><br>

<img width="740" height="316" src="http://eqvault.ign.com/screenshots/image.php?ss=684"/><p>

<font size=3>Calling themselves “The Bloodmoon,” after their leader, the great prophet Ralkor Bloodmoon, these lycopanthic orcs are a new clan splintered from the Crushbone orcs.  

Ralkor and his council of Moonfangs rule and coordinate the clan.  They reside in Bloodmoon Keep, the ruins of an ancient elven city in the Loping Plains that was destroyed centuries ago by Mayong Mistmoore.  Little is yet known about how the orcs contracted the curse of lycanthropy, but it certainly has done nothing to sate their thirst for blood and power.  The clan have been using their city as a base to expand their power beyond the Loping Hills and the Hills of Shade, eventually planning to envelope all of Faydwer.

The Bloodmoon have no allies, save the occasional convert from the Crushbone legions who wishes to embrace the gift of lycanthropy.  However, they are opposed by the fabled Fangbreakers who have worked to rid Norrath of Lycanthropes for years.</font><p>

<a href="http://eqplayers.station.sony.com/images/video/creatures/Wereorc_Magic.avi">Video of Wereorc Magic!</a><p>


<strong><font size=4><center>SHADES</strong></font></center><p>

<img width="509" height="317" src="http://eqvault.ign.com/screenshots/image.php?ss=681" /><p>

<font size=3>The shade creatures are the cursed spirits of previous inhabitants of the Hills of Shade and Loping Plains.  Long ago, the curse of a vengeful goddess destroyed the inhabitants and cursed them, transforming them into ghosts.  Most of the ghosts have gone insane after years of torment, but a few of them sometimes offer bits and pieces of advice and a glimpse into the past that caused their curse.  The power of these spirits varies greatly depending on the strength of will that the soul had when it was living, and they are all potentially dangerous.</font><p>

<a href="http://eqplayers.station.sony.com/images/video/creatures/Shade_Attack.avi">Video of a Shade Attack!</a><p>

<strong><font size=4><center>STEAMWORKS</strong></font></center><p>

<img width="740" height="316" src="http://eqvault.ign.com/screenshots/image.php?ss=682" /><p>

<font size=3>All of the new clockworks in this expansion were created by Meldrath the Malignant or one of his minions.  He has introduced steam power to the traditional clockwork, and therefore they are described as steamworks rather than clockworks.<p>

Steamworks are intelligent, nearly as smart as those that made them, and make up the bulk of Meldrath’s army and serve in all capacities, from grunt to warmarshal.  And while they are generally equal to their clockwork counterparts intellectually, they are on average much stronger and more dangerous than the generally peaceful clockworks of Ak’Anon.<p>

The steamworks are barracked on the flying island called Fortress Mechanotus and its attendant gyrospires.  But several of them were dislodged during battles with the gnomes of Steamfont and can be found scattered about Dragonscale Hills as a result.</font><p>

<a href="http://eqplayers.station.sony.com/images/video/creatures/Steamwork_Copter_Attack.avi">Video of a Copter Attack!</a><p>


<strong><font size=4><center>EXOSKELETONS</strong></font></center><p>
<img width="740" height="316" src="http://eqvault.ign.com/screenshots/image.php?ss=683" /><p>
 
<font size=3>The exoskeletons are a bit different, as they are steamwork machines directly controlled by gnomes.  These devices are dangerous, both for the enemy and for the driver, and are only used by Meldrath’s elite troops.  Some exoskeletons are used for special purposes outside of Meldrath’s Majestic Mansion, but most of them are kept inside Meldrath’s home where he can make use of them in an emergency.</font><p>

<a href="http://eqplayers.station.sony.com/images/video/creatures/Steamwork_Exoskeleton_Attack.avi">Video of an Exoskeleton Attack!</a><p>

<strong><font size=4><center>THE GUARDIAN</strong></font></center><p>

<img width="740" height="316" src="http://eqvault.ign.com/screenshots/image.php?ss=685" /><p>
 
<font size=3>The Guardian is a special case.  Meldrath built this enormous steamwork himself.  It is approximately one hundred feet tall and inside are dozens of rooms ranging from barracks to control rooms.  It’s probably more accurate to consider the Guardian as a hybrid of both steamwork and exoskeleton.  It has the appearance and basic motor movements of a steamwork, but it is controlled by its crew.<p>

Meldrath entrusted the Guardian to one of his very best soldiers and a rather large crew of mechanics, tinkers and soldiers and ordered them to use the Guardian to protect his mansion.  However, during the initial battle, the Guardian was thrown from the flying fortress and crashed into the Dragonscale Hills.  It wanders those hills endlessly, apparently lacking purpose.</font></p><p>

<a href="http://eqplayers.station.sony.com/images/video/creatures/Guardian_Walk.avi">Video of a Guardian Walking</a></td></tr></table></DIV>
